end, so don't feel like you need to write them down as I go.

251
00:13:03,703 --> 00:13:05,504
Also, if you don't want to buy books,

252
00:13:05,645 --> 00:13:08,547
there's actually a lot of advice on compositions online,

253
00:13:08,587 --> 00:13:11,069
so you don't need to get it, it's just a good one.

254
00:13:12,670 --> 00:13:15,873
One thing that book doesn't mention, however, is tangents.

255
00:13:16,593 --> 00:13:19,315
But if you search online for avoiding tangents in art,

256
00:13:19,395 --> 00:13:20,997
you'll find a lot of advice on it.

257
00:13:21,937 --> 00:13:25,100
And for anyone who wants to delve into the science

258
00:13:25,220 --> 00:13:27,862
of why tangents are a problem,

259
00:13:28,482 --> 00:13:31,185
there's a lot of good information in that book there.

260
00:13:33,315 --> 00:13:38,778
So as well as creating good compositions on screen, we also want to create depth on screen.

261
00:13:39,439 --> 00:13:43,301
So a screen by its nature is 2D, it's flat,

262
00:13:43,901 --> 00:13:48,064
which means that we need to use tips and tricks to trick the eye into seeing depth.

263
00:13:49,343 --> 00:13:52,184
One of the easiest techniques for doing this

264
00:13:52,384 --> 00:13:53,945
is creating layers.

265
00:13:54,505 --> 00:13:56,847
So by layers, I mean having foreground,

266
00:13:56,867 --> 00:13:58,427
mid-ground, and background elements.

267
00:13:59,408 --> 00:14:02,109
And what happens in the scene is what you see here.

268
00:14:02,469 --> 00:14:04,690
The foreground elements move at a different speed

269
00:14:04,731 --> 00:14:07,172
across the screen to the mid-ground and background

270
00:14:07,272 --> 00:14:07,692
elements.

271
00:14:08,212 --> 00:14:10,335
So this creates parallax animation,

272
00:14:10,455 --> 00:14:13,498
which is obviously what old school Disney animation uses.

273
00:14:14,179 --> 00:14:16,141
It's also an incredibly good way to make

274
00:14:16,682 --> 00:14:19,806
for very good bang for buck dynamic environments.

275
00:14:27,970 --> 00:14:30,393
So another way to create good depth on screen

276
00:14:31,314 --> 00:14:32,716
is with repeating elements.

277
00:14:33,196 --> 00:14:35,780
So if you have identical elements throughout the scene

278
00:14:36,320 --> 00:14:37,962
that are different depths in the scene,

279
00:14:39,164 --> 00:14:42,248
the player can use the relative sizes of those elements

280
00:14:42,568 --> 00:14:44,230
to judge the depth of the space.

281
00:14:48,480 --> 00:14:51,942
Another good way of creating depth is the use of atmospherics.

282
00:14:52,662 --> 00:14:56,365
So this is not part of our Pre-Vis and Pre-Production pass,

283
00:14:56,945 --> 00:15:00,507
but because it has such a big effect, it felt remiss not to mention it.

284
00:15:01,348 --> 00:15:04,289
So for anyone who doesn't know what atmospherics are, they are when

285
00:15:04,630 --> 00:15:08,652
particles in the atmosphere scatter the light and they make distant objects

286
00:15:08,932 --> 00:15:12,214
less distinct, and you get the kind of effect

287
00:15:12,254 --> 00:15:13,015
that you're seeing here.

288
00:15:15,155 --> 00:15:16,577
So for more on depth on screen,

289
00:15:16,677 --> 00:15:18,579
this here is a particularly good book.

290
00:15:20,502 --> 00:15:22,944
So as well as creating good compositions

291
00:15:23,024 --> 00:15:24,446
and creating depth on screen,

292
00:15:24,807 --> 00:15:27,710
we also want to control the shapes that we get on screen.

293
00:15:29,071 --> 00:15:29,512
So in,

294
00:15:31,359 --> 00:15:35,603
We can use the shapes on screen to create an emotional experience for the player.

295
00:15:36,184 --> 00:15:41,950
So in terms of evolution, different shapes have different emotional effects on us.

296
00:15:42,490 --> 00:15:48,677
So our ancestors who liked certain shapes that in nature were associated with safe things,

297
00:15:49,578 --> 00:15:52,261
those ancestors were more likely to survive and have us.

298
00:15:52,881 --> 00:15:58,424
Our ancestors who disliked shapes in nature that were associated with dangerous things,

299
00:15:58,864 --> 00:16:02,185
those ancestors were more likely to survive and have us.

300
00:16:02,705 --> 00:16:08,508
So we have inherited the likes and dislikes of our ancestors that helped them to survive.

301
00:16:09,188 --> 00:16:15,371
Now we can use those shapes and the emotional effect of those shapes to create an emotional

302
00:16:15,411 --> 00:16:16,491
experience for the player.

303
00:16:18,014 --> 00:16:23,179
So circular shapes in nature are associated with things which are safe and friendly.

304
00:16:23,339 --> 00:16:26,483
So think rolling hills, bushes, trees, that kind of thing.

305
00:16:27,724 --> 00:16:32,489
So they were used here in this particular one because this was something that the

306
00:16:32,509 --> 00:16:37,294
player was going to own and so we wanted a nice welcoming experience for the player.

307
00:16:38,015 --> 00:16:43,478
So you can see that the shapes are started in the previz,

308
00:16:43,938 --> 00:16:47,480
but they have been very much enhanced by the environment.

309
00:16:47,780 --> 00:16:52,803
Sorry, they've been, whoops, have some water.

310
00:16:56,945 --> 00:16:58,706
So the shapes have been very much enhanced

311
00:16:58,746 --> 00:17:00,747
by the interior artists who worked on it

312
00:17:00,827 --> 00:17:02,308
and the lighting artists as well.

313
00:17:04,303 --> 00:17:08,024
So jagged shapes in nature, these are dangerous things.

314
00:17:08,264 --> 00:17:11,986
So think broken rocks, broken sticks, broken bones,

315
00:17:13,506 --> 00:17:15,827
your teeth, claws, that kind of thing.

316
00:17:16,647 --> 00:17:19,689
So we can use those shapes to create unsettling experiences

317
00:17:19,769 --> 00:17:20,389
for the player.

318
00:17:20,709 --> 00:17:22,890
So it was very appropriate for a combat space

319
00:17:22,930 --> 00:17:25,211
where we wanted to create a tense situation.

320
00:17:26,091 --> 00:17:28,112
It is exacerbated in this situation

321
00:17:28,652 --> 00:17:30,873
by the top heavy nature of the architecture as well.

322
00:17:33,199 --> 00:17:41,269
So horizontal and vertical shapes are about power and control and stability. So a horizontal line,

323
00:17:41,530 --> 00:17:47,197
that's the horizon, so that's stable and unchanging. Vertical shapes think trees and

324
00:17:47,257 --> 00:17:52,043
cliffs, so they are powerful things but not necessarily as unchanging.

325
00:17:52,703 --> 00:17:55,744
So those shapes very much suited the storytelling

326
00:17:55,784 --> 00:17:58,285
of the situation where the player was playing

327
00:17:58,445 --> 00:18:02,586
as an office executive, and the idea was to give them

328
00:18:02,626 --> 00:18:04,606
a storytelling around power and control.

329
00:18:06,827 --> 00:18:09,768
So the shapes that end up on screen normally come

330
00:18:09,788 --> 00:18:11,368
from the previz, but not always.

331
00:18:11,828 --> 00:18:15,509
As you can see here, the curving lines on the floor

332
00:18:15,889 --> 00:18:17,730
are very much overriding the previz

333
00:18:17,790 --> 00:18:19,610
in terms of the final shapes on screen.

334
00:18:20,895 --> 00:18:24,778
You can also override the previz with things like,

335
00:18:24,918 --> 00:18:27,460
well, textures, patterns, and the lighting as well.

336
00:18:27,660 --> 00:18:29,581
So the shadows that you're getting from the lighting

337
00:18:29,941 --> 00:18:31,922
can make incredibly strong shapes on screen.

338
00:18:32,983 --> 00:18:37,406
Another thing to notice in this particular set of slides

339
00:18:38,046 --> 00:18:40,468
is that even though the architecture is very square

340
00:18:40,548 --> 00:18:43,870
in the previz, the shapes that we're getting on screen

341
00:18:43,970 --> 00:18:45,531
are actually very soft diagonals.

342
00:18:46,412 --> 00:18:48,453
The reason for this is obviously the angle

343
00:18:48,493 --> 00:18:49,994
that we're looking at the space from.

344
00:18:50,922 --> 00:18:54,324
Now, when I talked before about designing around choke points

345
00:18:54,384 --> 00:18:57,506
and through routes, one other thing to consider

346
00:18:57,666 --> 00:19:00,287
is that we actually decide where those choke points

347
00:19:00,347 --> 00:19:01,608
and through routes are going to be.

348
00:19:02,408 --> 00:19:05,590
So if we'd wanted to come into the space

349
00:19:05,690 --> 00:19:08,431
and make the first impression of it about power and control

350
00:19:08,472 --> 00:19:12,774
and stability, we would have come in front on to create

351
00:19:12,854 --> 00:19:14,134
square shapes on screen.

352
00:19:14,775 --> 00:19:18,997
If, however, we wanted a more informal introduction

353
00:19:19,077 --> 00:19:19,697
to the space.

354
00:19:20,979 --> 00:19:22,481
and something a little bit more dynamic,

355
00:19:22,802 --> 00:19:25,306
we can come in at a slight angle like you're seeing here.

356
00:19:27,410 --> 00:19:29,433
So, if you want to know more about shapes on screen,

357
00:19:29,613 --> 00:19:32,138
this here is a particularly lovely book on the topic.

358
00:19:33,897 --> 00:19:37,118
So to recap the controlling the 2D screen,

359
00:19:37,698 --> 00:19:42,120
so we want to compose the 3D for how it's going to look in 2D,

360
00:19:42,440 --> 00:19:44,541
and that is the one bit that differentiates us

361
00:19:44,601 --> 00:19:45,441
from other media.

362
00:19:45,861 --> 00:19:47,622
Everything else is just the advice

363
00:19:47,682 --> 00:19:49,583
that you're seeing for painting, photography,

364
00:19:49,603 --> 00:19:50,583
and cinematography.

365
00:19:50,943 --> 00:19:53,525
So that's things like creating good compositions,

366
00:19:54,225 --> 00:19:56,886
creating depth, and creating nice shapes on screen.

367
00:19:58,554 --> 00:20:00,755
So, movement. How do we control movement?

368
00:20:01,996 --> 00:20:04,797
Unfortunately, this section is going to be quite difficult,

369
00:20:04,857 --> 00:20:06,418
but if you'll just bear with me for it,

370
00:20:06,458 --> 00:20:08,159
the last section gets easy again.

371
00:20:09,180 --> 00:20:11,721
The reason for this is that controlling movement,

372
00:20:12,381 --> 00:20:14,322
well, the camera's attached to the player,

373
00:20:14,362 --> 00:20:17,023
so if we want to control where the camera looks and goes,

374
00:20:17,504 --> 00:20:19,885
we need to control, or at least try influence,

375
00:20:20,265 --> 00:20:21,586
where the player looks and goes.

376
00:20:23,600 --> 00:20:28,683
So, saliency is going to control where the player looks and therefore where the camera looks.

377
00:20:29,144 --> 00:20:33,086
Affordances will control where the player goes and therefore where the camera goes.

378
00:20:33,747 --> 00:20:38,970
Before I get into explaining what those terms actually mean, some quick myth busting first.

379
00:20:40,897 --> 00:20:45,599
So there is a concept in aesthetics that's been around for hundreds of years

380
00:20:46,140 --> 00:20:51,323
that a strong compositional line in a painting will lead the eye through the painting. So these

381
00:20:51,383 --> 00:20:57,326
are called leading lines. Now modern science has shown that this is not actually what's happening.

382
00:20:57,706 --> 00:21:01,429
What is happening is that our eyes are flicking past the compositional line

383
00:21:01,689 --> 00:21:04,951
and they're getting caught in it like a fish in a net. We're not.

384
00:21:05,491 --> 00:21:07,573
There is no directional element to it.

385
00:21:08,193 --> 00:21:10,856
Now, if our eyes are not following those composition lines,

386
00:21:11,256 --> 00:21:14,819
then we are not obviously physically following them either.

387
00:21:14,919 --> 00:21:16,741
There's no directional aspect to this.

388
00:21:18,194 --> 00:21:21,637
These lines are still incredibly good for capturing the player's attention.

389
00:21:22,138 --> 00:21:25,421
I also don't think we should throw out the concept of leading lines,

390
00:21:25,801 --> 00:21:30,725
because it is very useful in terms of understanding the structure of a 2D image.

391
00:21:31,326 --> 00:21:36,230
However, it is an abstraction, sorry, it is a spatialization of an abstract concept.

392
00:21:36,911 --> 00:21:39,934
So as humans, we quite often do this.

393
00:21:39,994 --> 00:21:42,496
We make spatializations of abstract concepts.

394
00:21:42,857 --> 00:21:45,419
So for example, I might refer to somebody

395
00:21:45,499 --> 00:21:47,461
as being in front of me or above me.

396
00:21:48,622 --> 00:21:51,445
That again, those are ways of spatializing

397
00:21:51,505 --> 00:21:52,485
something abstract.

398
00:21:53,006 --> 00:21:54,688
That is all that's happening here.

399
00:21:55,068 --> 00:21:56,629
By talking about leading lines,

400
00:21:56,830 --> 00:21:58,751
we are spatializing something abstract.

401
00:22:00,533 --> 00:22:02,354
It is still helpful to use, but we just

402
00:22:02,394 --> 00:22:04,035
need to remember that it's not literal,

403
00:22:04,575 --> 00:22:05,756
that the player is not lit.

404
00:22:05,976 --> 00:22:08,878
Their player's eyes are not literally traveling in a line.

405
00:22:09,298 --> 00:22:11,240
And therefore, we can't lead the player

406
00:22:11,400 --> 00:22:12,921
with a strong compositional line.

407
00:22:14,922 --> 00:22:16,363
Another thing that doesn't directly

408
00:22:16,423 --> 00:22:20,425
lead the player in terms of direct one-to-one,

409
00:22:20,526 --> 00:22:22,647
although it has an influence, is lighting.

410
00:22:23,407 --> 00:22:26,609
So what you're looking at here is an academic study

411
00:22:26,749 --> 00:22:28,671
on visual attention in 3D games.

412
00:22:29,467 --> 00:22:31,649
Now, at this moment in the study,

413
00:22:31,709 --> 00:22:33,791
the players were asked to exit the space.

414
00:22:34,752 --> 00:22:37,915
The correct exit was behind the lit bit of wall

415
00:22:37,955 --> 00:22:38,816
that you see there.

416
00:22:39,296 --> 00:22:42,079
The players had a lot of trouble finding that exit.

417
00:22:42,539 --> 00:22:44,741
They tried things like doors and fireplaces

418
00:22:44,921 --> 00:22:47,984
in spite of the fact that they were in darkness.

419
00:22:49,407 --> 00:22:53,328
Now this is because we don't automatically walk

420
00:22:53,488 --> 00:22:54,268
towards the light.

421
00:22:54,468 --> 00:22:56,869
If you think again about our evolutionary heritage,

422
00:22:57,369 --> 00:23:00,430
most of our evolving happened with sunlight.

423
00:23:00,910 --> 00:23:03,051
If you had a break in the clouds and a bit of light

424
00:23:03,091 --> 00:23:04,951
spilling through the clouds onto the ground,

425
00:23:05,211 --> 00:23:07,452
there's absolutely no reason that our ancestors

426
00:23:07,492 --> 00:23:09,452
should be walking towards that bit of ground.

427
00:23:09,912 --> 00:23:11,813
So we have not evolved to work in that way.

428
00:23:13,140 --> 00:23:17,588
What light can do, however, is it can help us see things that we might not otherwise see,

429
00:23:17,708 --> 00:23:20,713
and it can give spatial information that we might not otherwise have.

430
00:23:21,134 --> 00:23:25,562
So it is still very useful in leading the player, but it's just not a direct one-to-one.

431
00:23:28,496 --> 00:23:30,697
So something else, and this here is,

432
00:23:31,077 --> 00:23:33,198
I just want to give a bit of nuance on this one.

433
00:23:33,719 --> 00:23:35,860
So there is a concept called weenies,

434
00:23:35,980 --> 00:23:37,881
which a lot of you will be familiar with.

435
00:23:38,401 --> 00:23:40,622
And because every time I've given a test to this talk,

436
00:23:40,662 --> 00:23:42,023
people have asked me to spell it out.

437
00:23:42,303 --> 00:23:44,224
That's W-E-E-N-I-E-S.

438
00:23:45,025 --> 00:23:46,505
It is the German word for sausage.

439
00:23:48,707 --> 00:23:50,508
The term was coined by Walt Disney,

440
00:23:50,948 --> 00:23:53,369
and the idea is that a weenie leads the guest

441
00:23:53,469 --> 00:23:55,470
in the same way that a sausage leads a dog.

442
00:23:56,722 --> 00:23:58,062
Weenies absolutely work.

443
00:23:58,282 --> 00:23:59,503
Like, there's no doubt about it.

444
00:23:59,923 --> 00:24:02,924
But the reason they work is because of the mystery element.

445
00:24:03,505 --> 00:24:05,626
So weenies have two aspects to them.

446
00:24:05,706 --> 00:24:07,626
They are a landmark, and they have mystery.

447
00:24:08,127 --> 00:24:10,748
A landmark by itself is incredibly useful

448
00:24:10,808 --> 00:24:13,529
and incredibly important in terms of the way

449
00:24:13,589 --> 00:24:14,610
finding for the player.

450
00:24:14,910 --> 00:24:17,611
But if you want to actually lead the player to the landmark,

451
00:24:17,891 --> 00:24:18,952
you need to add mystery.

452
00:24:20,212 --> 00:24:21,753
I'm going to be talking about mystery later,

453
00:24:21,773 --> 00:24:23,213
so we will come back to this one.

454
00:24:24,774 --> 00:24:29,035
So myth busting over, how do we lead the player

455
00:24:29,095 --> 00:24:30,315
and therefore lead the camera?

456
00:24:31,056 --> 00:24:34,516
So saliency will control where the player looks

457
00:24:34,596 --> 00:24:35,957
and therefore where the camera looks.

458
00:24:36,397 --> 00:24:38,737
Affordances will control where the player goes

459
00:24:38,857 --> 00:24:40,258
and therefore where the camera goes.

460
00:24:41,378 --> 00:24:43,198
So let's starting with saliency.

461
00:24:43,639 --> 00:24:46,519
So saliency is a scientific term which means attention.

462
00:24:46,959 --> 00:24:48,600
So something that is highly salient

463
00:24:48,700 --> 00:24:50,460
is something that is attention grabbing.

464
00:24:51,450 --> 00:24:52,912
There are two types of saliency.

465
00:24:53,052 --> 00:24:54,693
We have bottom-up and top-down.

466
00:24:55,234 --> 00:24:58,776
So bottom-up saliency is all about contrast.

467
00:24:59,157 --> 00:25:02,259
So it's contrast of color, it's contrast of size,

468
00:25:02,700 --> 00:25:06,123
contrast of shape, contrast of orientation,

469
00:25:06,683 --> 00:25:09,886
contrast of texture, and that's the bottom left-hand corner,

470
00:25:09,906 --> 00:25:13,589
that one's a bit more subtle, and contrast of movement.

471
00:25:16,341 --> 00:25:18,363
Top-down saliency, on the other hand,

472
00:25:18,423 --> 00:25:19,905
is about things which are meaningful.

473
00:25:20,365 --> 00:25:23,168
So human faces are always highly salient to us

474
00:25:23,208 --> 00:25:24,490
because they are meaningful to us.

475
00:25:25,030 --> 00:25:27,013
Humans in general are always highly salient

476
00:25:27,033 --> 00:25:28,194
because, again, they are meaningful.

477
00:25:29,095 --> 00:25:31,898
Things which are associated with a current task or goal,

478
00:25:31,958 --> 00:25:33,460
so if I am playing a ball game,

479
00:25:33,760 --> 00:25:36,283
then a ball shape is going to be very salient to me.

480
00:25:37,444 --> 00:25:40,268
If I'm getting ready for work, then shoe shapes will be salient.

481
00:25:40,729 --> 00:25:44,294
If I'm thirsty, then shapes associated with drinks will be salient.

482
00:25:44,755 --> 00:25:49,441
And of course, there are some things which are always salient to us because they affect things like safety.

483
00:25:51,174 --> 00:25:54,138
So the final saliency, so where our attention is going,

484
00:25:54,218 --> 00:25:56,641
is a mix of both bottom-up and top-down.

485
00:25:57,663 --> 00:25:59,205
How much comes from bottom-up

486
00:25:59,285 --> 00:26:00,746
and how much comes from top-down

487
00:26:01,127 --> 00:26:02,849
depends on what mode that we're in.

488
00:26:03,410 --> 00:26:05,613
So the more we are in a task-orientated

489
00:26:05,713 --> 00:26:07,055
or goal-orientated mode,

490
00:26:07,455 --> 00:26:09,918
the more top-down saliency is dominating.

491
00:26:11,272 --> 00:26:13,093
Now, this is quite important for video games

492
00:26:13,193 --> 00:26:15,813
because obviously our players are usually

493
00:26:15,893 --> 00:26:18,754
in a very task-orientated or goal-orientated mode.

494
00:26:19,394 --> 00:26:21,834
This means that compared to other media,

495
00:26:21,954 --> 00:26:24,415
the top-down saliency is going to be much stronger.

496
00:26:24,975 --> 00:26:27,035
So in film, where people are just sitting there

497
00:26:27,055 --> 00:26:29,616
and watching a film, the bottom-up saliency

498
00:26:29,916 --> 00:26:33,096
will be stronger because people are just in a relaxed mode.

