00:39:45,548 --> 00:39:48,110
in nonviolent moments of action games.

747
00:39:49,895 --> 00:39:51,856
So as we talked about before,

748
00:39:52,096 --> 00:39:54,056
mystery also attracts the player.

749
00:39:54,696 --> 00:39:57,017
How this is working in terms of affordances

750
00:39:57,557 --> 00:40:01,638
is that the affordance is that there is information

751
00:40:01,678 --> 00:40:02,558
for us to learn.

752
00:40:03,078 --> 00:40:06,019
As humans, we very much like learning information.

753
00:40:06,799 --> 00:40:11,280
So what is going on here is that the castle in this case

754
00:40:11,780 --> 00:40:13,820
is promising us that if we move closer,

755
00:40:14,381 --> 00:40:15,681
there will be more for us to learn.

756
00:40:16,061 --> 00:40:22,126
Now how it is doing it in this particular situation is with the very interesting profile and with the

757
00:40:22,286 --> 00:40:28,011
extra detail on the architecture that tells us that there is stuff to discover if we get closer.

758
00:40:28,611 --> 00:40:33,215
The secondary prospect that I was talking about before, that is also about mystery.

759
00:40:33,535 --> 00:40:38,619
If we move closer to that spot we will get a view and of course a view is information.

760
00:40:40,959 --> 00:40:44,682
So as well as simple object affordances,

761
00:40:45,062 --> 00:40:47,244
surface affordances, complex affordances,

762
00:40:47,364 --> 00:40:51,707
and spatial affordances, we also have wayfinding elements.

763
00:40:52,288 --> 00:40:55,871
So a quick recap here for anyone who doesn't know.

764
00:40:56,551 --> 00:40:58,533
So there are five types of wayfinding elements.

765
00:40:59,033 --> 00:41:00,374
We have landmarks.

766
00:41:00,614 --> 00:41:02,856
These are individual objects which stand out.

767
00:41:03,236 --> 00:41:06,038
So think a church spire or a mountain.

768
00:41:06,999 --> 00:41:07,980
We have districts.

769
00:41:08,400 --> 00:41:11,203
Districts are areas with their own flavour.

770
00:41:11,403 --> 00:41:15,126
So think Chinatown, the Wharf, Central Business District,

771
00:41:15,226 --> 00:41:15,927
that kind of thing.

772
00:41:16,908 --> 00:41:20,311
Linear elements are, or paths, sorry,

773
00:41:20,651 --> 00:41:22,773
are linear elements which afford movement.

774
00:41:23,013 --> 00:41:25,716
So think a path, obviously, but also a road.

775
00:41:26,096 --> 00:41:28,898
If you're in a boat, then a river would be a path.

776
00:41:29,599 --> 00:41:31,000
If you're in a car, then a motorway.

777
00:41:32,458 --> 00:41:36,081
So edges are linear elements which prevent movement.

778
00:41:36,341 --> 00:41:37,742
So think of a wharf.

779
00:41:38,442 --> 00:41:39,683
Also think again of the river,

780
00:41:39,743 --> 00:41:42,725
but this time if you're traveling in a car.

781
00:41:43,526 --> 00:41:44,866
And think again of a motorway,

782
00:41:44,906 --> 00:41:46,868
but this time if you're traveling on foot.

783
00:41:47,468 --> 00:41:49,489
So these are very context dependent

784
00:41:49,549 --> 00:41:50,750
in terms of how you're traveling.

785
00:41:52,064 --> 00:41:53,185
And then we have nodes.

786
00:41:53,766 --> 00:41:56,209
Nodes are moments of decision or choice.

787
00:41:56,910 --> 00:42:00,114
So think of an intersection, a town square,

788
00:42:00,594 --> 00:42:03,718
but also think of things like a airport or a train station.

789
00:42:04,919 --> 00:42:06,541
So this

790
00:42:09,269 --> 00:42:11,450
As I mentioned before, wayfinding elements

791
00:42:11,630 --> 00:42:13,570
don't directly lead the player,

792
00:42:13,830 --> 00:42:17,231
but they do affect the mental map the players have,

793
00:42:17,311 --> 00:42:19,872
and that mental map affects where the players will go.

794
00:42:20,612 --> 00:42:22,372
So to give you an example,

795
00:42:22,913 --> 00:42:24,873
if you were to give someone direction

796
00:42:24,933 --> 00:42:26,673
somewhere pre-Google map days,

797
00:42:27,334 --> 00:42:28,654
you might say something like this.

798
00:42:29,274 --> 00:42:31,175
Follow this road till you get to the tree.

799
00:42:31,635 --> 00:42:32,815
At the tree, turn left.

800
00:42:32,995 --> 00:42:35,296
Once you cross the river, it's the red door on your right.

801
00:42:36,376 --> 00:42:38,496
There, I just used wayfinding elements.

802
00:42:39,117 --> 00:42:41,398
So the road that we were on was a path,

803
00:42:41,519 --> 00:42:43,100
the tree was a landmark,

804
00:42:43,600 --> 00:42:45,421
the river that we crossed was an edge,

805
00:42:45,882 --> 00:42:48,664
and the red door was another landmark at a different scale.

806
00:42:49,384 --> 00:42:51,246
So what we're doing is we are structuring

807
00:42:51,286 --> 00:42:52,627
our understanding of a space

808
00:42:52,787 --> 00:42:54,088
around these different elements.

809
00:42:54,989 --> 00:42:57,010
And it is our understanding of a space

810
00:42:57,050 --> 00:42:58,912
that will affect how we move through a space.

811
00:42:59,573 --> 00:43:02,755
Now this is absolutely something that could easily

812
00:43:02,816 --> 00:43:04,277
be a whole talk in its own right,

813
00:43:04,297 --> 00:43:05,438
so I'm going to leave it there.

814
00:43:06,719 --> 00:43:09,061
But if you want to know more about wayfinding elements,

815
00:43:09,682 --> 00:43:12,144
this here is the book that those originally come from.

816
00:43:12,804 --> 00:43:16,628
And there's quite a lot of interesting modern science

817
00:43:17,488 --> 00:43:20,071
on how we do spatial mapping.

818
00:43:20,451 --> 00:43:22,633
So that there is a particularly good article.

819
00:43:23,154 --> 00:43:24,455
There was also a talk on Monday,

820
00:43:24,515 --> 00:43:26,857
which unfortunately you've missed if you didn't go to it,

821
00:43:27,318 --> 00:43:28,559
but I'm sure it'll be on the vault.

822
00:43:29,520 --> 00:43:32,263
But yeah, that was also a good talk on spatial mapping.

823
00:43:34,147 --> 00:43:36,129
So to recap the movement section,

824
00:43:36,729 --> 00:43:40,752
so saliency or attention will control

825
00:43:40,772 --> 00:43:43,314
where the player looks and therefore where the camera looks.

826
00:43:43,534 --> 00:43:45,135
We had two types of saliency.

827
00:43:45,175 --> 00:43:47,077
We had bottom-up and we had top-down.

828
00:43:47,977 --> 00:43:50,379
And again, the top-down saliency is stronger

829
00:43:50,859 --> 00:43:55,903
when people are in a task-orientated or goal-orientated mode.

830
00:43:56,684 --> 00:44:01,267
Affordances are controlling where the player goes and therefore where the camera goes.

831
00:44:01,887 --> 00:44:08,172
So we had simple object affordances, surface affordances, complex affordances,

832
00:44:08,232 --> 00:44:10,573
spatial affordances and wayfinding elements.

833
00:44:12,262 --> 00:44:15,144
So, moving on to the final section, now time.

834
00:44:15,604 --> 00:44:18,986
So, time in film would normally be controlled

835
00:44:19,046 --> 00:44:20,568
with the camera or with editing.

836
00:44:21,108 --> 00:44:23,930
For us, we obviously aren't directly controlling

837
00:44:23,950 --> 00:44:25,851
the camera apart from what control we,

838
00:44:26,632 --> 00:44:28,073
what guidance we can give the player,

839
00:44:28,953 --> 00:44:31,035
and we don't have editing outside of cut scenes.

840
00:44:32,516 --> 00:44:34,978
Luckily for us, space is experienced over time.

841
00:44:34,998 --> 00:44:35,038
So,

842
00:44:37,189 --> 00:44:39,811
When I take in this room, I don't take it all in

843
00:44:39,951 --> 00:44:41,592
in one instant, in one moment.

844
00:44:41,712 --> 00:44:44,014
I take it in because my eye is traveling over it

845
00:44:44,134 --> 00:44:45,735
or I'm physically walking through it,

846
00:44:46,095 --> 00:44:48,477
or in a video game, my avatar might be walking through it.

847
00:44:49,017 --> 00:44:51,719
This means that what is laid out over space

848
00:44:51,839 --> 00:44:53,681
is actually experienced over time.

849
00:44:54,081 --> 00:44:56,082
So we can set things up in space

850
00:44:56,163 --> 00:44:58,184
that we want to be experienced over time.

851
00:45:00,246 --> 00:45:03,328
One major element of this is repetition and rhythm.

852
00:45:03,908 --> 00:45:06,270
So in film, they would often do editing

853
00:45:06,950 --> 00:45:09,191
to get different types of rhythm.

854
00:45:09,331 --> 00:45:11,432
So you might have much faster editing

855
00:45:11,813 --> 00:45:13,994
to create an intense moment in the film.

856
00:45:15,275 --> 00:45:21,079
So we can set up rhythm with architectural repetition.

857
00:45:21,660 --> 00:45:24,242
So repeating elements architecturally

858
00:45:24,502 --> 00:45:26,824
will be experienced as a rhythm over time.

859
00:45:27,505 --> 00:45:29,726
So if you look at these columns here,

860
00:45:29,906 --> 00:45:32,368
you don't again take them in all in one instant

861
00:45:32,408 --> 00:45:33,049
in one moment.

862
00:45:33,349 --> 00:45:36,072
You take them in over time as your eye travels over them.

863
00:45:36,593 --> 00:45:41,237
We can change the layout of that rhythm,

864
00:45:41,658 --> 00:45:46,203
of the architecture, to change the type of rhythm

865
00:45:46,243 --> 00:45:46,763
we're getting.

866
00:45:46,964 --> 00:45:49,246
Now that is easiest explained on a little mock-up.

867
00:45:49,927 --> 00:45:53,729
So you can see that the columns on the left

868
00:45:54,730 --> 00:45:56,991
are much closer together than the columns on the right

869
00:45:57,051 --> 00:46:00,514
and create a much more intense rhythm than the columns

870
00:46:00,554 --> 00:46:01,034
on the right.

871
00:46:01,394 --> 00:46:04,676
So we can change the density over space

872
00:46:05,237 --> 00:46:07,818
to affect the intensity over time.

873
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:12,201
So for more on the architectural side of this,

874
00:46:12,341 --> 00:46:14,183
this here is a particularly good book.

875
00:46:15,621 --> 00:46:18,265
Now, as with anything that involves intensity,

876
00:46:18,325 --> 00:46:20,689
this is something that we want to change over time.

877
00:46:21,955 --> 00:46:24,497
So to be constantly at high intensity

878
00:46:24,537 --> 00:46:26,498
can get a little bit overwhelming for the player,

879
00:46:27,218 --> 00:46:29,039
and they can also become numb to it.

880
00:46:29,939 --> 00:46:32,981
And to be at a low intensity constantly

881
00:46:33,381 --> 00:46:34,501
can become a bit boring.

882
00:46:34,742 --> 00:46:36,242
So we want to change things up.

883
00:46:36,743 --> 00:46:39,604
And again, changing things up in terms of intensity

884
00:46:39,664 --> 00:46:41,485
over time means changing things up

885
00:46:41,605 --> 00:46:43,566
in terms of density over space.

886
00:46:44,006 --> 00:46:47,508
So we don't want to have the same kind of layouts

887
00:46:47,608 --> 00:46:50,309
and patterns throughout our spaces.

888
00:46:50,349 --> 00:46:51,250
We want to vary them.

889
00:46:52,850 --> 00:46:54,731
So as well as rhythm and repetition,

890
00:46:54,771 --> 00:46:56,532
we also want to think about transitions.

891
00:46:57,172 --> 00:46:59,473
So in film, this would be how you go

892
00:46:59,513 --> 00:47:00,734
from one shot to the next.

893
00:47:01,194 --> 00:47:03,535
So that might be a cut or it might be a dissolve,

894
00:47:04,635 --> 00:47:07,436
or a few other things as well, but those are the main ones.

895
00:47:07,876 --> 00:47:11,898
So again, for us, what is happening over space

896
00:47:11,958 --> 00:47:13,279
is experienced over time.

897
00:47:13,659 --> 00:47:16,680
So we can do this through our spatial layouts.

898
00:47:17,501 --> 00:47:20,744
So the classic example here would be Disneyland.

899
00:47:21,325 --> 00:47:24,208
So what they do when you go between spaces in Disneyland

900
00:47:24,308 --> 00:47:26,731
is they create stylistic transitions.

901
00:47:27,472 --> 00:47:28,473
So what you're looking at,

902
00:47:28,733 --> 00:47:31,176
the red arrows are elements of one style.

903
00:47:31,196 --> 00:47:33,418
It is a little bit hard to see, I'm afraid,

904
00:47:33,458 --> 00:47:35,280
but you can always go to Disneyland.

905
00:47:35,801 --> 00:47:35,901
See?

906
00:47:36,562 --> 00:47:37,482
Yeah.

907
00:47:38,162 --> 00:47:41,203
So the red elements are, the red arrows

908
00:47:41,243 --> 00:47:42,904
are pointing to elements of one style,

909
00:47:43,044 --> 00:47:44,825
the yellow to elements of the other style.

910
00:47:44,945 --> 00:47:47,526
So they're things like lamp posts and handrails

911
00:47:47,906 --> 00:47:49,486
and stuff like that that it's pointing to.

912
00:47:49,586 --> 00:47:51,667
And the orange one doesn't fit either.

913
00:47:52,628 --> 00:47:55,290
As you can see, there isn't an abrupt transition.

914
00:47:55,930 --> 00:48:00,033
They slowly stop one and introduce another.

915
00:48:00,193 --> 00:48:02,315
So there are moments right in the middle there

916
00:48:02,695 --> 00:48:05,237
where you actually get lampposts of one style

917
00:48:05,617 --> 00:48:08,219
that are sitting over the top of handrails of another style.

918
00:48:08,860 --> 00:48:12,643
So they are creating stylistic dissolves between area.

919
00:48:12,763 --> 00:48:15,665
And again, they're laying them out over space,

920
00:48:16,105 --> 00:48:17,646
but they are experienced over time.

921
00:48:19,332 --> 00:48:21,594
So we can do this architecturally as well.

922
00:48:22,355 --> 00:48:24,358
So what you're looking at here,

923
00:48:24,418 --> 00:48:27,822
so this was done for the After Hours DLC.

924
00:48:28,583 --> 00:48:32,167
So these two very different architectural styles

925
00:48:32,208 --> 00:48:33,769
that you're looking at, pardon me.

926
00:48:35,540 --> 00:48:38,103
They were supposed to belong to the same space.

927
00:48:38,823 --> 00:48:41,846
So the first one, the reason we used

928
00:48:41,886 --> 00:48:44,228
the post and beam industrial style architecture

929
00:48:44,588 --> 00:48:46,349
was because this was supposed to be a club

930
00:48:46,610 --> 00:48:48,631
and this was the kind of spaces

931
00:48:49,532 --> 00:48:51,814
that you saw in those types of clubs.

932
00:48:52,835 --> 00:48:56,418
However, the final one with the curving architectural style,

