00:49:05,288 --> 00:49:09,031
the reason for that was that it was a storage space

937
00:49:09,432 --> 00:49:11,634
and it would just be incredibly boring

938
00:49:11,674 --> 00:49:13,676
to have a post and beam architectural style

939
00:49:13,716 --> 00:49:15,217
for a storage space.

940
00:49:15,738 --> 00:49:17,740
And we try very much not to do boring.

941
00:49:18,721 --> 00:49:22,863
So what the architect who worked on this, what she did,

942
00:49:23,364 --> 00:49:27,766
was she created a transitional area between the two.

943
00:49:28,507 --> 00:49:32,729
So the office area, which sat between these two spaces,

944
00:49:33,650 --> 00:49:36,431
we had, well, she had created,

945
00:49:37,872 --> 00:49:40,634
she had both elements from both styles.

946
00:49:40,694 --> 00:49:41,634
So there were the curves

947
00:49:41,774 --> 00:49:43,415
and there were the post and beam elements.

948
00:49:43,875 --> 00:49:45,777
And now suddenly the spaces actually feel

949
00:49:45,797 --> 00:49:46,797
like they belong together.

950
00:49:48,432 --> 00:49:52,095
So for more on different types of ways

951
00:49:52,115 --> 00:49:53,876
you can transition architecturally,

952
00:49:54,737 --> 00:49:56,278
this here is the book to go to.

953
00:49:56,739 --> 00:49:58,400
This is definitely a book to dip into

954
00:49:58,460 --> 00:50:00,282
rather than to try read cover to cover.

955
00:50:01,343 --> 00:50:02,864
Luckily for us with architecture,

956
00:50:02,904 --> 00:50:05,526
we actually have a lot more options here compared to film.

957
00:50:07,548 --> 00:50:08,909
To give you another example,

958
00:50:09,029 --> 00:50:11,011
if you were to say walk into a building

959
00:50:11,051 --> 00:50:12,072
straight off the street,

960
00:50:12,212 --> 00:50:15,034
so there's just a door directly on the street,

961
00:50:15,094 --> 00:50:16,475
that would be the equivalent of a cut.

962
00:50:17,256 --> 00:50:21,800
If you added some elements like a veranda or similar between the door and the street,

963
00:50:22,340 --> 00:50:25,983
you would create more of a dissolve. There are a lot, and I do mean a lot,

964
00:50:26,103 --> 00:50:31,248
of different ways we can move between spaces architecturally. And yes, that's the book to go to.

965
00:50:32,248 --> 00:50:34,010
So, to recap the whole talk now.

966
00:50:35,030 --> 00:50:39,714
So we were looking at the fact that even though we can't control the camera,

967
00:50:40,014 --> 00:50:42,757
we can control the environment that the player moves through.

968
00:50:43,137 --> 00:50:48,322
This means that we can create cinematic experiences by controlling the environment.

969
00:50:49,140 --> 00:50:53,904
So with the 2D screen, we are composing the 3D

970
00:50:54,004 --> 00:50:55,605
for how it looks in 2D.

971
00:50:55,745 --> 00:50:57,847
That was the main thing that was, oh, thank you.

972
00:50:58,768 --> 00:51:00,829
That was the main thing that was differentiating us

973
00:51:00,869 --> 00:51:03,211
from other media, and beyond that,

974
00:51:03,772 --> 00:51:06,193
everything else was just the normal advice

975
00:51:06,213 --> 00:51:07,434
that you get in other media.

976
00:51:07,855 --> 00:51:09,616
So it was creating good compositions,

977
00:51:09,676 --> 00:51:10,737
it was creating depth,

978
00:51:10,797 --> 00:51:12,638
and it was creating nice shapes on screen.

979
00:51:14,584 --> 00:51:16,666
With the movement section,

980
00:51:16,866 --> 00:51:19,048
that was about saliency and affordances.

981
00:51:19,628 --> 00:51:21,970
So saliency is controlling where the player is

982
00:51:22,030 --> 00:51:23,912
looking and therefore where the camera is looking.

983
00:51:24,352 --> 00:51:26,854
We had bottom-up saliency and top-down saliency.

984
00:51:27,314 --> 00:51:30,237
Affordances are controlling where the player is going,

985
00:51:30,317 --> 00:51:31,858
and therefore where the camera is going.

986
00:51:32,158 --> 00:51:34,480
For that, we had object affordances,

987
00:51:34,540 --> 00:51:37,262
surface affordances, spatial affordances,

988
00:51:37,883 --> 00:51:39,224
and wayfinding elements.

989
00:51:39,644 --> 00:51:42,225
With time, space is experienced over time,

990
00:51:42,626 --> 00:51:44,947
so we can set up spatially what we want

991
00:51:44,987 --> 00:51:46,467
to be experienced over time.

992
00:51:47,148 --> 00:51:49,629
So this was rhythm and repetition

993
00:51:49,649 --> 00:51:50,750
was one of the main elements,

994
00:51:50,810 --> 00:51:53,111
but also controlling our transitions.

